  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Warning to the World
  author: Seok Naeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The sun rises in the east as the moon sets in the west—
    In this human realm, death and life take countless forms.
    We exhale our last breath, three inches of vital air,
    And add but one more pile of earth upon the mountainside.

    Who awakens first to the clamor of worldly attachments?
    The karma and consciousness drift boundless, losing the way.
    To escape the wheel of rebirth, there is no other method—
    Cling to the patriarch's koan, that medicine for awakening.

    Cold and heat take turns hastening us; the months and years flow on.
    How many times do we taste joy? How many times do we grieve?
    At last we become white bones beneath the green grass,
    And all the gold in the world cannot buy back our youth.

    After death, we cling to regrets that echo through ages,
    Yet while we live, who has the will to rest even a moment?
    The sages and worthies were all once ordinary beings—
    Why not follow the path they forged and practice as they did?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three inches of vital air' refers to the final breath at death in Buddhist tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'patriarch's koan' references Zen Buddhist practice, where a koan (hwadu in Korean) serves as a paradoxical utterance to provoke enlightenment.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem contrasts the permanence of natural cycles with human mortality, a common theme in Buddhist-influenced Korean poetry.
